contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

14:27.450 --> 14:28.884
How's the skull coming along?

14:28.918 --> 14:30.152
More slowly than I

14:30.186 --> 14:31.653
or Dr. Brennan would want.

14:31.688 --> 14:33.655
The missing pieces
aren't helping, either.

14:33.690 --> 14:36.658
Well, I'm sure
you'll do a fine job.

14:36.693 --> 14:39.461
That was oddly polite.

14:39.495 --> 14:41.596
Yeah.

14:41.631 --> 14:43.865
Sorry. I...

14:49.172 --> 14:51.006
This may not be
the time or the place,

14:51.040 --> 14:54.209
but I think it's better
if I didn't go to dinner

14:54.243 --> 14:55.644
with you and your parents.

14:55.678 --> 14:57.045
How would that be better?
I love you.

14:57.080 --> 14:58.146
I want them to meet you.

14:58.181 --> 14:59.381
Well, you love
your parents, too.

14:59.415 --> 15:01.783
And what they think means
a lot to you.

15:01.818 --> 15:03.018
Cam...
You told me what happened when

15:03.052 --> 15:04.186
your brother introduced

15:04.220 --> 15:05.554
his girlfriend.
They broke up, right?

15:05.588 --> 15:08.824
That was different.
You hope.

15:08.858 --> 15:10.359
But I don't want to be
there when you're forced

15:10.393 --> 15:12.661
to choose between them or me.

15:12.695 --> 15:15.030
Have a little faith in me.

15:15.064 --> 15:17.699
Unless you're too scared.

15:17.734 --> 15:19.701
What's that supposed to mean?

15:19.736 --> 15:21.370
BRENNAN: I have the results
of the histological.

15:21.404 --> 15:24.906
What do you notice
about the findings, Mr. Vaziri?

15:26.976 --> 15:28.643
There's no crystallization.

15:28.678 --> 15:30.212
Precisely.
What exactly

15:30.246 --> 15:31.947
does that mean?
Well, normally when a body

15:31.981 --> 15:33.148
is frozen, ice crystals
form from the water

15:33.182 --> 15:34.716
in the body,
rupturing the cells.

15:34.751 --> 15:36.218
The histological shows
there is no rupturing.

15:36.252 --> 15:37.386
But if the body wasn't frozen,

15:37.420 --> 15:39.054
then none of our findings
make sense.

15:39.088 --> 15:40.088
That is not my conclusion.

15:40.123 --> 15:41.857
The victim was frozen,

15:41.891 --> 15:43.358
but also vitrified.

15:43.393 --> 15:44.793
The water in the
body is replaced

15:44.827 --> 15:46.161
by cryoprotective chemicals,

15:46.195 --> 15:48.163
which is why
there were no ice crystals.

15:48.197 --> 15:50.165
She was cryogenically frozen?

15:50.199 --> 15:53.201
At temperatures well below
negative 100 degrees Celsius.

15:53.236 --> 15:55.103
Which explains
why the organs fractured.

15:55.138 --> 15:57.906
It actually explains
everything we've seen.

15:57.940 --> 15:59.975
Except who killed her and how.

16:03.379 --> 16:06.615
BOOTH: <i>Look, there's a</i>
<i>cryo-whatever-you-call-it place</i>

16:06.649 --> 16:07.816
in Vienna, Virginia,
just a block from where

16:07.850 --> 16:08.817
she took her bus trips.

16:08.851 --> 16:10.419
And it's called cryonics.

16:10.453 --> 16:12.821
It's the low-temperature
preservation of humans

16:12.855 --> 16:15.724
with the hope
that resuscitation

16:15.758 --> 16:17.392
may be possible
in the future.

16:17.427 --> 16:18.827
It's nuts, okay?
When you die,

16:18.861 --> 16:20.829
it's ashes to ashes,
not ashes to ice.

16:20.863 --> 16:23.064
We all search for immortality
in our own way.

16:23.099 --> 16:25.367
It's what binds
tribes and religions.

16:25.401 --> 16:28.570
Just please tell me that
you're not gonna want me

16:28.604 --> 16:30.038
to freeze you.

16:30.072 --> 16:31.940
No, but

16:31.974 --> 16:33.809
one day you might
be able to download

16:33.843 --> 16:36.044
my accumulated consciousness
onto a memory chip.

16:36.078 --> 16:37.512
Listen.

16:37.547 --> 16:40.282
Let's just, you know,
keep each other in here.

16:40.316 --> 16:43.652
That's worked just
fine for a long time.

16:43.686 --> 16:46.822
You know, Christine and I

16:46.856 --> 16:48.924
could come to Germany, too.

16:48.958 --> 16:50.459
But you know I wouldn't
ask you to do that.

16:50.493 --> 16:51.493
Your work is here.

16:51.527 --> 16:53.161
So, you'd stand in the way

16:53.196 --> 16:57.065
of us having a new and possibly
life-changing experience?

16:57.099 --> 16:59.634
That seems selfish, Booth.

17:00.837 --> 17:02.971
What, you'd really
uproot everything?

17:03.005 --> 17:06.040
Wouldn't you?

17:09.612 --> 17:11.413
BOOTH:
<i>I kind of figured this place</i>

17:11.446 --> 17:13.248
would be more hospitally, right?

17:13.281 --> 17:15.250
A little bit more,
I don't know, sterile?

17:15.284 --> 17:18.185
Cryonics operations have
very little funding.

17:18.221 --> 17:20.355
Most of their funding comes

17:20.388 --> 17:22.557
from member donations.

17:22.592 --> 17:24.159
Member donations?

17:24.193 --> 17:25.926
I don't know if they
have a lot of members.

17:25.962 --> 17:27.429
Actually, we have over 700

17:27.463 --> 17:30.832
full- and part-time members.
Right. And you are...?

17:30.867 --> 17:32.567
I am Dr. Noah Summers.
This is my wife, Michelle.

17:32.602 --> 17:34.503
We own CryoNova.

17:34.537 --> 17:35.670
Your turn.

17:35.705 --> 17:37.205
FBI Special Agent
Seeley Booth.

17:37.240 --> 17:38.773
This here is my partner,
Dr. Temperance Brennan.

17:38.808 --> 17:40.475
Dr. Brennan.

17:40.510 --> 17:42.477
I'm thrilled that you're
interested in our services.

17:42.512 --> 17:43.979
It would be my honor
to preserve your brain.

17:44.013 --> 17:45.580
BRENNAN:
I'm sure it would.

17:45.615 --> 17:47.382
But at this point, cryonics is

17:47.416 --> 17:48.917
nothing more than a fantasy.

17:48.951 --> 17:49.951
MICHELLE:
As is often the case

17:49.986 --> 17:52.153
before great discoveries.

17:52.188 --> 17:53.688
So if you're not interested
in being preserved,

17:53.723 --> 17:55.357
how can we help you?

17:55.391 --> 17:56.958
Do you know a woman by the name
of Madeline Papadelis?

17:56.993 --> 17:58.126
Of course.

17:58.160 --> 17:59.327
She used to visit all the time.

17:59.362 --> 18:01.496
Her daughter is one
of our patients.

18:01.531 --> 18:03.632
BOOTH:
Her daughter is dead.

18:03.666 --> 18:06.134
Technically she's in a state
of suspended animation.

18:06.168 --> 18:08.303
Well, not her mother.
Technically, she is dead dead.

18:08.337 --> 18:10.605
She was found in a swamp
outside Alexandria.

18:10.640 --> 18:12.207
What?
BRENNAN: And all the evidence indicates

18:12.241 --> 18:14.442
that she was
cryogenically frozen.

18:15.037 --> 18:17.171
Here.

18:18.563 --> 18:20.525
We haven't seen
Madeline in months.

18:20.526 --> 18:21.593
She used to come here
every Saturday

18:21.627 --> 18:22.961
to visit her daughter.

18:22.995 --> 18:25.296
Her daughter who is
dead who isn't dead.

18:25.331 --> 18:26.998
Yes, Madeline was dedicated
to our cause.

18:27.032 --> 18:29.367
She and I were working on
a proposal for a funding grant.

18:29.401 --> 18:31.569
And then she just disappeared.

18:31.604 --> 18:32.871
We tried to contact her,
but she never answered

18:32.905 --> 18:34.772
her voice mails or texts.

18:34.807 --> 18:36.574
We waived the storage
fees for her daughter

18:36.609 --> 18:38.209
until we could locate her.

18:38.244 --> 18:39.677
Man, these tanks are huge.

18:39.712 --> 18:42.013
I mean, why do you need so
much space for one body?

18:42.047 --> 18:43.214
Well, we can store
up to five

18:43.249 --> 18:44.816
whole body preservations

18:44.850 --> 18:46.484
in one dewar.

18:46.519 --> 18:48.186
Or a couple dozen neuros.

18:48.220 --> 18:50.314
Neuros?
Heads.

18:50.315 --> 18:51.448
They remove
and freeze the head.

18:51.482 --> 18:52.950
Don't need to know that. Okay.

18:52.984 --> 18:54.251
You know what? You guys
are in the business

18:54.285 --> 18:56.119
of freezing people.
The victim was frozen.

18:56.154 --> 18:57.347
So therefore,
I need to shut you down.

18:57.348 --> 18:58.448
No.
God, no.

18:58.790 --> 19:00.324
We have patients to care for.

19:00.358 --> 19:01.725
We have others contracted to come in.
So?

19:01.759 --> 19:02.793
Why aren't you
talking to Warshaw?

19:02.827 --> 19:04.194
We've already lodged

19:04.229 --> 19:05.929
a complaint with the police,
and so has Madeline.

19:05.964 --> 19:07.864
Who is Warshaw?
Tripp Warshaw.

19:07.899 --> 19:09.299
He's another cryonicist
in Maryland.

19:09.300 --> 19:11.401
He stored patients
in his garage.

19:11.436 --> 19:12.569
Garage?

19:12.604 --> 19:13.870
Wait a second, wait.

19:13.905 --> 19:16.106
Who licenses you guys,
Frankenstein?

19:16.140 --> 19:18.408
They're licensed
as cemeteries,

19:18.443 --> 19:19.643
which have
very little oversight.

19:19.677 --> 19:20.978
Warshaw went
out of business.

19:21.012 --> 19:22.446
Blamed us for taking
his patients.

19:22.480 --> 19:23.847
Including Madeline's daughter.

19:23.881 --> 19:25.115
He shot out our lock
and tried to break in

19:25.149 --> 19:26.683
and sabotage the facility.

19:26.718 --> 19:27.851
I can show you.

19:27.885 --> 19:29.386
All right, look,
was he arrested?

19:29.420 --> 19:30.520
No, they said

19:30.555 --> 19:32.022
there wasn't enough proof.

19:32.056 --> 19:34.358
But now with Madeline's death?

19:34.392 --> 19:36.760
You should talk to him.

19:36.794 --> 19:38.495
Hmm.

19:38.529 --> 19:40.697
SAROYAN: <i>I'm gonna need you both</i>
<i>to go to CryoNova.</i>

19:40.732 --> 19:43.533
Angela, I'm gonna need you
to access their digital records.

19:43.568 --> 19:45.168
And, Hodgins,
I need you to catalog

19:45.203 --> 19:46.637
any drugs and chemicals
they used.

19:46.671 --> 19:48.338
Wait, drugs?

19:48.373 --> 19:49.973
They're dead when they're
frozen, aren't they?

19:50.008 --> 19:51.508
Yes, but they keep
oxygen circulating

19:51.542 --> 19:52.942
while putting
in the cryoprotectants

19:52.944 --> 19:56.380
to save the cellular
integrity of the remains.

19:56.414 --> 19:57.748
And they use propofol
to keep the remains

19:57.782 --> 19:59.016
from animating
during the process.

19:59.050 --> 20:00.284
Animating?

20:00.318 --> 20:02.719
You-you mean
like the walking dead?

20:02.754 --> 20:04.121
Yeah, it's actually...

20:04.155 --> 20:05.455
If you say cool,
you won't have sex

20:05.490 --> 20:06.590
for, like, a year.

20:06.624 --> 20:07.958
Revolting.

20:07.992 --> 20:09.326
It's totally revolting.

20:09.360 --> 20:10.494
Are you ready?

20:10.528 --> 20:13.196
One second.

20:13.231 --> 20:15.432
Well, the dinner is on, huh?

20:15.466 --> 20:17.734
Does everyone know about this?
Absolutely.

20:17.769 --> 20:20.103
It's all we can talk about.
So I'm not the only one who's

20:20.138 --> 20:21.705
a little sensitive
around their parents?

20:21.739 --> 20:23.106
Okay, then.

20:23.141 --> 20:24.875
You can cut me
a little slack.

20:24.909 --> 20:26.510
This is gonna be fine, right?

20:26.544 --> 20:27.577
Right, 'cause you didn't make

20:27.612 --> 20:29.112
this seem awful at all.

20:29.147 --> 20:31.114
You're not going to make
this easy on me, are you?

20:31.149 --> 20:32.916
MONTENEGRO: Okay, you
guys should probably go.

20:32.950 --> 20:34.651
Parents don't like
when the kids are late.

20:34.686 --> 20:36.887
Right.
Right.

20:39.524 --> 20:40.457
It's gonna be fine.

20:40.491 --> 20:43.160
Right.

20:43.194 --> 20:45.462
(quiet laugh)

20:47.065 --> 20:50.033
BRENNAN:
<i>Madeline Papadelis</i>

20:50.068 --> 20:52.736
was going to place her daughter
in your care originally,

20:52.770 --> 20:54.538
wasn't she, Mr. Warshaw?

20:54.572 --> 20:57.174
Before CryoNova
poached her, yeah.

20:57.208 --> 20:59.576
So, you blame them
for your business going under.

20:59.610 --> 21:01.945
All they care
about is the bottom line.

21:01.979 --> 21:04.014
I'm all about the science,
and not just cryonics,

21:04.048 --> 21:06.516
but biological immortality.

21:06.551 --> 21:08.418
I'm currently studying
the tardigrades,

21:08.453 --> 21:10.520
which are extremophiles.

21:10.555 --> 21:11.688
You-you believe
there's a connection

21:11.723 --> 21:13.857
between them
and cellular senescence

21:13.891 --> 21:16.159
as a function
of chronological age?

21:16.194 --> 21:17.294
We're all made out
of the same stuff.

21:17.328 --> 21:19.096
Ah, hold it
there, pal, okay?

21:19.130 --> 21:21.565
I am definitely not made out of
the same stuff as you, trust me.

21:21.599 --> 21:23.834
Actually we're all
carbon-based organisms.

21:23.868 --> 21:26.169
Really? Do we have
to discuss that right now?

21:26.204 --> 21:28.171
It's not the time. So, we looked
at your credit report, Tripp.

21:28.206 --> 21:29.773
It turns out that

21:29.807 --> 21:31.842
every business
that you bought equipment from

21:31.876 --> 21:33.810
is suing you.
I owed money.

21:33.845 --> 21:36.012
Because CryoNova poached
all my clients.

21:36.047 --> 21:38.148
Because Madeline backed out.

21:38.182 --> 21:41.218
Her daughter was your last hope.

21:41.252 --> 21:43.420
Wasn't she?

21:43.454 --> 21:45.822
You got angry.
Wouldn't you be angry?

21:45.857 --> 21:47.257
I was working with new methods,

21:47.291 --> 21:48.592
better methods

21:48.626 --> 21:50.093
of cryonic stabilization.

21:50.128 --> 21:51.795
Is that why you shot
your way into CryoNova?

21:51.829 --> 21:53.063
I didn't!

21:53.097 --> 21:54.798
The police never
arrested me for that.

21:54.832 --> 21:55.899
I understand someone standing

21:55.933 --> 21:57.467
in the way of new discoveries.

21:57.502 --> 21:59.803
Researchers and professors
often assault one another.

21:59.837 --> 22:01.972
Murder is not unheard of.

22:03.274 --> 22:04.408
Murder?

22:04.442 --> 22:05.742
BOOTH:
Madeline.

22:05.777 --> 22:07.477
Four months ago.
Then she was frozen.

22:07.512 --> 22:08.945
BRENNAN:
And then discarded

22:08.980 --> 22:10.547
four days ago,
when you were finally

22:10.581 --> 22:13.784
supposed to have
your equipment repossessed.

22:22.026 --> 22:23.794
Arastoo has told
Armin and myself

22:23.828 --> 22:25.862
a great deal about you.

22:25.897 --> 22:27.397
All good, I hope,
Khanome Vaziri.

22:27.432 --> 22:28.331
Don't call me that...

22:28.366 --> 22:30.434
Mamaan.

22:31.636 --> 22:34.404
I meant, call me Azita.

22:35.506 --> 22:37.941
ARMIN:
You are a surgeon,

22:37.975 --> 22:40.243
Dr. Saroyan?
Oh, please, call me Cam.

22:40.278 --> 22:41.745
I told you,
she's a coroner,

22:41.779 --> 22:43.213
which is a very respected
profession, Baba.

22:43.247 --> 22:44.448
SAROYAN:
I can speak

22:44.482 --> 22:45.715
for myself, Arastoo.

22:45.750 --> 22:48.819
So you handle dead bodies,
as our son does.

22:48.853 --> 22:50.120
SAROYAN:
Yes.

22:50.154 --> 22:51.955
Although he focuses
more on bones.

22:51.989 --> 22:54.691
I deal more with tissue
and organs and stuff.

22:54.725 --> 22:56.927
I-It's probably not
dinner conversation.

22:56.961 --> 22:58.995
We're here to get to know
each other, aren't we?

22:59.030 --> 23:00.831
I've told my son

23:00.865 --> 23:02.232
I can't imagine

23:02.266 --> 23:04.801
being consumed with death
all the time.

23:04.836 --> 23:07.170
SAROYAN: Oh, there's so much more
to our lives than death.

23:07.205 --> 23:09.639
We go to concerts and museums,

23:09.674 --> 23:11.775
and we laugh...

23:13.010 --> 23:15.645
I know that look.

23:17.181 --> 23:19.182
Do you plan on having children?

23:19.217 --> 23:20.484
Oh...

23:20.518 --> 23:22.986
None of you
are getting any younger.

23:23.020 --> 23:24.855
Mamaan.
You should apologize.

23:24.889 --> 23:27.190
Now biology is
your mother's fault?

23:27.225 --> 23:28.725
SAROYAN:
I actually already

23:28.759 --> 23:30.627
have a daughter.
She's in college.

23:30.661 --> 23:32.462
ARMIN:
Oh.

23:32.497 --> 23:34.030
You were married before.

23:34.065 --> 23:35.298
SAROYAN:
No, she's the, um...

23:35.333 --> 23:36.900
child of
a man

23:36.934 --> 23:38.835
that I lived with
for a few years.

23:38.870 --> 23:40.170
He passed away...

23:40.204 --> 23:41.838
It's, uh, complicated.
I love her

23:41.873 --> 23:43.240
very much,

23:43.274 --> 23:45.575
and your son
is wonderful with her.

23:46.711 --> 23:48.545
Funny that he didn't mention

23:48.579 --> 23:50.247
that he had a child in his life.

23:50.281 --> 23:52.883
Perhaps I didn't want
the questions and judgments.

23:54.919 --> 23:57.587
So you keeping secrets--
this is also our fault.

23:57.622 --> 24:00.290
Can I take your order?
Yes, please. Um...

24:00.324 --> 24:02.659
I haven't even looked
at the menu yet.

24:03.828 --> 24:06.596
Do you have
someplace else to go?

24:08.466 --> 24:10.433
I'll give you another minute.

24:12.870 --> 24:15.839
I imagine Persian food
is quite foreign to you.

24:15.873 --> 24:17.040
SAROYAN:
Arastoo is actually

24:17.074 --> 24:18.308
quite a good cook.

24:18.342 --> 24:19.876
His, uh, Ghalieh Mahi
is my favorite.

24:19.911 --> 24:21.611
ARMIN:
Mamaan taught him.

24:21.646 --> 24:24.214
I'm surprised
you like it.

24:24.248 --> 24:26.716
Cultural differences can
sometimes be difficult to...

24:26.751 --> 24:28.818
Fine.
We get it.

24:28.853 --> 24:31.021
We're too different from each other.
She-she has a child,

24:31.055 --> 24:33.823
our professions are repulsive,
it'll never work.

24:33.858 --> 24:35.725
Well, I love her. And that's all
that matters to me.

24:35.760 --> 24:38.528
(speaking Farsi): 
I won't let you two destroy

24:38.563 --> 24:40.363
my relationship
with my girlfriend

24:40.398 --> 24:41.865
with your old-fashioned
thoughts, the way you did

24:41.899 --> 24:43.833
with Hamid.
You aren't ashamed when you talk

24:43.868 --> 24:45.602
to me like this?
No, I am not ashamed. Why should I?

24:45.636 --> 24:47.237
No, he didn't destroy;
you guys did it.

24:47.271 --> 24:48.705
Who? We destroyed Hamid's
relationship or Hamid did it

24:48.739 --> 24:49.939
with himself?
Who did it, then?

24:49.941 --> 24:51.174
Arastoo, don't do this!
No, you guys destroyed

24:51.208 --> 24:52.175
his life.
You make me embarrassed

24:52.209 --> 24:53.476
in front of other people.
Let's go.

24:53.511 --> 24:54.878
Just go, be ashamed.

24:54.912 --> 24:57.581
Go. Go.
Um, wow, it was nice to meet you.

25:20.237 --> 25:22.439
Have you been here
all night, Mr. Vaziri?

25:22.473 --> 25:23.907
Most of the
night, yeah.

25:23.941 --> 25:26.610
Cam is pretty upset, so...

25:26.644 --> 25:27.911
Because of your parents?

25:27.945 --> 25:29.713
Yes.

25:29.747 --> 25:31.448
I believe on some level

25:31.482 --> 25:33.516
our parents are supposed
to disappoint us

25:33.551 --> 25:35.018
so we can

25:35.052 --> 25:36.820
surpass them
and improve the species.

25:36.854 --> 25:39.089
So put your dinner
in perspective.

25:39.123 --> 25:40.657
It was an
evolutionary necessity.

25:40.691 --> 25:41.791
I understand

25:41.826 --> 25:43.393
you found something?
I did.

25:43.427 --> 25:45.428
There's an excessive
amount of exfoliation

25:45.463 --> 25:47.530
on this tibia.
Huh.

25:49.967 --> 25:51.968
There does
appear to be

25:52.003 --> 25:53.570
significantly
more flaking

25:53.604 --> 25:55.672
on the cortical bone
than I would expect to see.

25:55.706 --> 25:57.040
Did you find it
anywhere else?

25:57.074 --> 25:59.209
The metatarsals and tarsals
of the same leg.

25:59.243 --> 26:00.477
The excessive

26:00.511 --> 26:02.145
yet isolated exfoliation

26:02.179 --> 26:03.713
indicates a lack of equilibrium

26:03.748 --> 26:05.715
in the vitrification process.

26:05.750 --> 26:07.517
The perfusion of
the cryoprotectant

26:07.551 --> 26:08.952
at the time of freezing wasn't completed?
Precisely.

26:08.986 --> 26:10.453
The killer either
used equipment

26:10.488 --> 26:12.155
that hadn't been
serviced properly,

26:12.189 --> 26:13.390
or he was in a rush.

26:13.424 --> 26:14.924
And the skull?

26:14.959 --> 26:16.459
Dr. Hodgins is still picking
things out of the muck.

26:16.494 --> 26:18.228
If he doesn't find
any more bone fragments,

26:18.262 --> 26:19.629
this is all we'll have.

26:20.631 --> 26:22.565
SWEETS:
<i>So it turns out</i>

26:22.600 --> 26:24.167
Tripp Warshaw
was in Phoenix

26:24.201 --> 26:25.468
when the victim
disappeared.

26:25.503 --> 26:27.037
He was working at some
longevity institute.

26:27.071 --> 26:28.505
Well, that makes sense,
because ballistics says

26:28.539 --> 26:29.873
the bullet wasn't his.

26:29.907 --> 26:31.547
It was from a gun
owned by the ex-husband?

26:31.575 --> 26:32.842
Yeah. I'm gonna
go talk to him now.

26:32.877 --> 26:34.544
Booth.
Uh...

26:34.578 --> 26:35.879
so the deputy director's office

26:35.913 --> 26:37.681
asked me to take a look
at your military record,

26:37.715 --> 26:39.783
factor that into my analysis.

26:39.817 --> 26:40.917
<i>The</i> deputy director?
Yeah.

26:40.951 --> 26:42.285
So it <i>is</i> moving up.

26:42.319 --> 26:43.687
Mm-hmm. You don't seem

26:43.721 --> 26:45.088
too happy about that.
Look, all the reports

26:45.122 --> 26:46.589
that they have
me looking at

26:46.624 --> 26:48.124
are from other shootings,
from other agents.

26:48.159 --> 26:49.559
They want to know how
I would have handled them.

26:49.593 --> 26:50.860
Because of
your past.

26:50.895 --> 26:52.135
That's probably why they had me

26:52.163 --> 26:53.697
take a look at
your military record.

26:53.731 --> 26:55.165
I'm sure there aren't
a lot of candidates

26:55.199 --> 26:56.399
with your skill set.

26:56.434 --> 26:58.435
Exactly.

26:58.469 --> 27:01.004
Sit down, Ethan.

27:02.940 --> 27:04.674
Look, you lied to us.

27:04.709 --> 27:06.609
Why didn't you tell us that
your daughter was frozen?

27:06.644 --> 27:08.611
That is nobody's business but mine.
It is my business

27:08.646 --> 27:10.680
when you shoot up
the facility that she was stored in.

27:10.715 --> 27:12.282
She shouldn't
be in there.

27:12.316 --> 27:14.718
She should be buried
the way God intended.

27:14.752 --> 27:16.119
Why did you lie to me?
Because I've got two strikes,

27:16.153 --> 27:17.620
felony assault,
against me.

27:17.655 --> 27:20.490
One more and
I'm going away for real time.

27:20.524 --> 27:22.158
What do you think
you're going to be facing

27:22.193 --> 27:23.760
when I charge you with
the murder of your ex-wife?

27:23.794 --> 27:25.762
I went in there
to get Karine.

27:25.796 --> 27:27.230
To bury her proper.

27:27.264 --> 27:28.865
But have you
seen that place?

27:28.899 --> 27:31.167
All those metal things?
I couldn't figure out

27:31.202 --> 27:32.370
how to get my baby out of there.

27:32.395 --> 27:33.269
And when that didn't
work out for you,

27:33.270 --> 27:35.805
the only thing left for you
to do was get revenge.

27:35.840 --> 27:37.440
If I couldn't think
how to get Karine

27:37.475 --> 27:39.008
out of one
of those things,

27:39.043 --> 27:41.611
how the hell could I have
put Madeline into one?

27:45.249 --> 27:46.916
You wanted
to see me?

27:46.951 --> 27:49.552
I reviewed the security footage
from CryoNova.

27:49.587 --> 27:51.921
Let me pull it up.

27:51.956 --> 27:54.791
I heard dinner
wasn't so good.

27:54.825 --> 27:56.593
Ugh. Dinner would
imply food.

27:56.627 --> 27:58.094
We didn't get that far.

27:58.129 --> 27:59.929
But we're trying to put it
all behind us,

27:59.964 --> 28:01.765
so I'd rather not talk
about it at work.

28:01.799 --> 28:02.999
Sure.

28:03.033 --> 28:04.834
Okay, so...

28:04.869 --> 28:06.770
look who Madeline
was arguing with

28:06.804 --> 28:08.705
the Saturday before
she was killed.

28:08.739 --> 28:10.340
SAROYAN: What are they
arguing about?

28:10.374 --> 28:12.008
MONTENEGRO:
There's no sound.

28:12.042 --> 28:14.177
But look at this.

28:18.649 --> 28:21.251
SAROYAN: Holy... Okay,
what is happening?

28:23.821 --> 28:26.656
Your guess is
as good as mine.

28:33.164 --> 28:35.832
Madeline was a true believer.

28:35.866 --> 28:37.433
If she caught Noah
messing around

28:37.468 --> 28:39.202
with the patients
in his charge...

28:39.236 --> 28:41.304
He looks like a monster.

28:41.338 --> 28:43.840
God only knows
what he would do.

28:45.487 --> 28:47.199
Madeline caught you
sawing into patients

28:47.200 --> 28:48.868
and threatened to turn you in.
Do you know how much

28:48.902 --> 28:52.078
a full body preservation costs?
$200,000.

28:52.232 --> 28:53.900
When that patient's wife died,

28:53.934 --> 28:55.968
payments stopped.
BOOTH: Okay, great.

28:56.003 --> 28:57.804
So what were you doing?
Just sawing up patients

28:57.838 --> 28:59.639
to make room for
a new popsicle?

28:59.673 --> 29:00.940
I needed
the space,

29:00.974 --> 29:02.608
but I was preserving his brain,

29:02.643 --> 29:04.243
which is really
all that matters.

29:04.278 --> 29:06.446
Because by the time we're
able to reanimate people,

29:06.480 --> 29:07.720
we'll be giving
them new bodies.

29:07.748 --> 29:08.981
Better bodies.

29:09.016 --> 29:10.316
You were harvesting his organs.

29:10.350 --> 29:11.951
To sell them.
Yes.

29:11.985 --> 29:13.186
They have done successful

29:13.220 --> 29:14.821
cryo transplants of kidneys.

29:14.855 --> 29:16.722
That's how I got the funds
to keep his brain stored.

29:16.757 --> 29:18.958
Selling body parts,
that's not in your contract.

29:18.992 --> 29:20.359
If Madeline exposed you,

29:20.394 --> 29:22.034
that could destroy your business.
Madeline

29:22.062 --> 29:24.363
was committed to the work.

29:24.398 --> 29:25.631
She understood
the necessity

29:25.666 --> 29:27.166
of keeping the
facility solvent.

29:27.201 --> 29:28.367
Look at the last grant proposal

29:28.402 --> 29:29.735
that we worked on together.

29:29.770 --> 29:31.537
It mentions organ sales.
BOOTH: Right. Okay.

29:31.572 --> 29:33.439
So, uh, cutting up people
and selling their parts,

29:33.474 --> 29:35.274
all of a sudden
that's a good thing now?

29:35.309 --> 29:36.476
BRENNAN: Well, it could save
people's lives,

29:36.510 --> 29:38.678
if the organs are
frozen properly.

29:38.712 --> 29:40.012
You're on his side now?
Agent Booth,

29:40.047 --> 29:41.647
everything
that I do,

29:41.682 --> 29:42.815
my life's work,

29:42.850 --> 29:44.951
is dedicated
to preventing death.

29:44.985 --> 29:46.953
I would never
kill anyone.

29:46.987 --> 29:50.823
Especially someone as close
to me as Madeline was.

29:56.163 --> 29:57.997
HODGINS: So it has to be
either Tripp Warshaw

29:58.031 --> 29:59.232
or the guys
from CryoNova.

29:59.266 --> 30:00.566
SAROYAN:
Seems reasonable.

30:00.601 --> 30:02.235
Well, the ex-husband's not out.

30:02.269 --> 30:04.570
He studied pre-med in college,
so he's not as dumb

30:04.605 --> 30:06.839
about this whole process
as he wants us to believe.

30:06.874 --> 30:08.114
How does someone
go from pre-med

30:08.142 --> 30:09.375
to having two strikes
against them?

30:09.409 --> 30:11.277
Drugs.

30:11.311 --> 30:13.045
Although he's been
in recovery for the past two years.

30:13.080 --> 30:14.447
Well, so he says.

30:14.481 --> 30:15.982
People are not always
who they seem to be.

30:16.016 --> 30:18.184
Are we talking
about the case now

30:18.218 --> 30:19.860
or are we talking about
dinner last night?

30:19.885 --> 30:20.620
Wow.

30:20.621 --> 30:23.022
You do not give up, do you?
You really have to ask her that?

30:23.056 --> 30:26.025
You know, I felt
bad for Arastoo.

30:26.059 --> 30:28.094
He had this notion that
when I met the folks,

30:28.128 --> 30:30.596
it was gonna be all
rainbows and unicorns.

30:30.631 --> 30:31.931
That never sounded good to me.

30:31.965 --> 30:33.445
I mean, unicorns,
they seem dangerous,

30:33.467 --> 30:34.834
with the horn and everything...

30:37.304 --> 30:38.638
Not really the
point. Sorry.

30:38.672 --> 30:40.039
Continue.

30:40.073 --> 30:41.674
So they didn't
approve of you?

30:41.708 --> 30:43.142
Arastoo wouldn't let it
get that far, I guess.

30:43.177 --> 30:44.817
That's why we left.
You would have stayed?

30:44.845 --> 30:47.079
He knows them.
I don't.

30:47.114 --> 30:48.481
I just, I feel terrible

30:48.515 --> 30:50.816
being the source of all
of this hostility.

30:50.851 --> 30:52.084
Isn't this a little sexy,
though?

30:52.119 --> 30:53.953
I mean, him
defending your love

30:53.987 --> 30:55.721
at any cost?

30:56.924 --> 30:58.090
Wait a minute.

30:58.125 --> 31:00.393
If the husband
did freeze Madeline,

31:00.427 --> 31:02.028
he could have
put her in a dewar

31:02.062 --> 31:03.362
and the Summers
might not have known.

31:03.397 --> 31:05.865
Until new clients
needed to be frozen.

31:05.899 --> 31:07.500
Yeah, they'd have
to get rid of Madeline

31:07.534 --> 31:10.937
before they were arrested
for murder.

31:10.971 --> 31:13.739
HODGINS: Those were the last four bone
fragments buried in the muck.

31:13.774 --> 31:14.369
Nothing more?

31:14.394 --> 31:16.342
Anything else probably
sunk into the swamp

31:16.343 --> 31:18.044
or was carried off by predators.

31:18.078 --> 31:19.612
I did find this, though.

31:19.646 --> 31:21.814
It's synthetic
multi-filament thread.

31:21.848 --> 31:23.216
Tied.

31:25.052 --> 31:26.419
Stitches.
The victim had to

31:26.453 --> 31:27.653
have been injured
before she was killed.

31:27.688 --> 31:28.888
There's no
record of her

31:28.922 --> 31:30.923
visiting a hospital
or a doctor.

31:30.958 --> 31:32.325
Dr. Brennan,
feel this.

31:35.028 --> 31:36.329
I see what you
mean, Mr. Vaziri.

31:36.363 --> 31:37.697
You do?

31:37.731 --> 31:39.498
The hole has curved,
smooth edges.

31:39.533 --> 31:41.968
That injury was not caused by
trauma during the body dump.

31:42.002 --> 31:44.036
That part of the skull
was removed surgically.

31:44.071 --> 31:45.705
Yes. This is
a cranial

31:45.739 --> 31:47.740
perforation with the
express purpose

31:47.774 --> 31:49.734
of placing a microphone
inside the victim's skull.

31:49.743 --> 31:52.712
Wait... what?
To listen for cracking as she froze,

31:52.746 --> 31:54.847
to protect the brain.
They're actually referred to

31:54.881 --> 31:56.482
as crackphones.

31:56.516 --> 31:57.850
This is an excellent find,

31:57.884 --> 31:59.752
Mr. Vaziri.
Wow. Focusing on your work

31:59.786 --> 32:02.288
to avoid personal issues
has its rewards.

32:02.322 --> 32:05.358
Yes, I often use work
to avoid my personal life.

32:06.793 --> 32:08.261
Implanting
a crackphone

32:08.295 --> 32:10.596
would require great skill.

32:10.631 --> 32:12.064
I doubt the ex-husband
could accomplish this,

32:12.099 --> 32:14.166
even with some
medical training.

32:14.201 --> 32:15.635
CryoNova must have audio records
from their crackphones.

32:15.669 --> 32:16.969
Well, doesn't
that mean

32:17.004 --> 32:18.638
the other cryo guy,
Tripp Warshaw,

32:18.672 --> 32:20.273
would have audio records, too?

32:23.377 --> 32:25.578
BOOTH: All of Warshaw's
equipment was repossessed

32:25.612 --> 32:27.046
and all the bodies
that were there,

32:27.080 --> 32:28.447
they were sent to another
company in New York.

32:28.482 --> 32:30.149
And the audio from
the crackphones?

32:30.183 --> 32:32.118
Ah, it was all erased when
the equipment was returned.

32:32.152 --> 32:34.220
You're missing a good, old-fashioned
murder, aren't you?

32:34.254 --> 32:35.655
Oh, come on.
Aren't you?

32:35.689 --> 32:36.956
We're all sitting
around here, hoping that

32:36.990 --> 32:38.190
someone recorded
a confession

32:38.225 --> 32:39.925
into some frozen
lady's head.

32:39.960 --> 32:43.629
And that's only if CryoNova kept
their audio files.

32:43.664 --> 32:46.499
The records at CryoNova show
that a family of four came in

32:46.533 --> 32:49.468
seven days ago for processing.
There was a car accident.

32:49.503 --> 32:51.304
So they had to make
room for them.

32:51.338 --> 32:53.873
Exactly. One of the dewars had
to be cleaned and prepped.

32:53.907 --> 32:56.309
Well, the crackphones
at CryoNova exist in a sleep mode.

32:56.343 --> 32:58.978
They only get activated
when noise is made.

32:59.012 --> 33:01.013
So the audio files
still exist.

33:01.048 --> 33:04.984
Yeah. And I don't think CryoNova's
gonna be very happy about it.

33:05.018 --> 33:08.220
I enhanced the audio.

33:08.255 --> 33:11.590
WOMAN: I knew what was going on
with you, bitch.

33:11.625 --> 33:13.726
(wheeled cart rolling)

33:13.760 --> 33:15.294
Sound's like someone's removing
the victim's body

33:15.329 --> 33:16.829
from one of the dewars.

33:16.863 --> 33:19.365
To dispose of it because
new bodies were coming in.

33:19.399 --> 33:21.167
Who is it?

33:21.201 --> 33:23.302
I think this next part
will make that pretty clear.

33:23.337 --> 33:27.673
WOMAN: Noah is mine, not yours.
It's time we finally end this.

33:27.708 --> 33:28.974
Michelle Summers.

33:29.009 --> 33:30.643
Madeline must've
been having an affair

33:30.677 --> 33:32.545
with her husband.
Yeah. I think

33:32.579 --> 33:35.114
Mrs. Frankenstein
is your killer.

33:38.864 --> 33:41.132
I knew what was going on
with you, bitch.

33:41.166 --> 33:45.025
Noah is mine, not yours.
It's time we finally end this.

33:45.026 --> 33:47.027
Hey, look, that was
time-stamped a week ago

33:47.062 --> 33:50.197
when Madeline Papadelis' body
was dumped in the swamp.

33:50.232 --> 33:51.599
That proves nothing.

33:51.633 --> 33:53.434
I believe I was talking
to another employee

33:53.468 --> 33:55.736
as I was prepping
one of the dewars.

33:55.771 --> 33:57.638
She was flirting
with my husband.

33:57.672 --> 33:59.473
If your job was prepping
the dewars,

33:59.508 --> 34:02.143
that means that you knew that
Madeline was being stored there.

34:02.177 --> 34:04.458
Our patients are stored in bags
and suspended upside down.

34:04.479 --> 34:07.314
One of those fibers from the bags
was found on her body.

34:07.349 --> 34:08.748
Your husband and
Madeline spent

34:08.784 --> 34:10.184
a lot of time together,
didn't they?

34:10.185 --> 34:11.552
We've been
through this.

34:11.585 --> 34:13.420
They wrote grant proposals
together.

34:13.455 --> 34:14.989
She was helping him raise money.

34:15.023 --> 34:17.291
You know, on our warrant,
we were able to look

34:17.324 --> 34:20.860
not only at your husband's
personal e-mails on his computer

34:20.896 --> 34:22.963
but also CryoNova's.

34:22.998 --> 34:24.465
Yeah, there are
eight e-mails here

34:24.498 --> 34:26.500
where your husband asked
Madeline if they could meet privately.

34:26.534 --> 34:28.536
My husband and I are
very much in love.

34:28.570 --> 34:30.271
Really? Because
on these two here,

34:30.304 --> 34:32.139
he asked to meet her at a motel.

34:32.174 --> 34:33.841
And they're all dated
four months ago.

34:33.875 --> 34:35.743
When Madeline disappeared,

34:35.777 --> 34:38.179
they worked together closely,
they were falling in love.

34:38.213 --> 34:39.847
You saw an
opportunity

34:39.880 --> 34:41.549
and you took it.

34:41.583 --> 34:43.284
Tell you what.
If you help us out,

34:43.318 --> 34:45.018
the prosecutor
is going to be much more

34:45.053 --> 34:46.253
understanding on you.

34:46.288 --> 34:48.255
I will not be manipulated
like this.

34:48.290 --> 34:50.391
I want a lawyer.

34:57.566 --> 34:58.999
Michelle Summers will be
released

34:59.034 --> 35:00.801
if we don't find evidence

35:00.836 --> 35:02.503
that links her directly
to the murder.

35:02.537 --> 35:04.805
She can be held
for the disposal of the remains.

35:04.840 --> 35:06.941
But our job
is to arrest a murderer.

35:06.975 --> 35:09.610
The lack of perimortem
injuries suggests the murderer

35:09.644 --> 35:10.878
was not violent.

35:10.912 --> 35:12.813
The killer took care
not to cause her pain.

35:12.848 --> 35:14.582
That doesn't sound like a jealous wife.
I agree,

35:14.616 --> 35:16.217
especially considering
she was anesthetized

35:16.251 --> 35:17.384
with chloroform first.

35:17.419 --> 35:18.485
But Michelle Summers was

35:18.520 --> 35:19.753
a professional; she'd know how

35:19.788 --> 35:21.088
to kill someone
without leaving

35:21.122 --> 35:22.322
evidence of a violent assault.

35:22.324 --> 35:23.390
That doesn't explain

35:23.425 --> 35:24.525
why she took care

35:24.559 --> 35:25.999
to cryogenically preserve
the victim.

35:26.027 --> 35:28.362
And why insert the crackphone?

35:28.396 --> 35:31.565
She wouldn't want to reanimate
a woman she hated.

35:31.600 --> 35:33.467
Look at the hole
in the temporal

35:33.501 --> 35:35.502
where the crackphone
was inserted.

35:35.537 --> 35:37.738
Feel the beveling.

35:37.772 --> 35:39.573
The angle of the incision.

35:39.608 --> 35:42.109
It had to have been made
by a left-handed person.

35:42.143 --> 35:44.245
Michelle Summers
is right-handed.

35:44.279 --> 35:46.247
I don't understand.

35:46.281 --> 35:47.882
Her husband must be left-handed.

35:47.916 --> 35:50.150
No one else would take such care
after a murder.

35:50.185 --> 35:52.052
Because, to him,
this wasn't a murder.

35:55.090 --> 35:56.690
We know it was you
who froze her.

35:56.725 --> 35:58.192
Absurd.

35:58.226 --> 35:59.693
We rewatched the video

35:59.728 --> 36:01.795
of you removing the
frozen kidney,

36:01.830 --> 36:03.631
and we noticed something.

36:03.665 --> 36:05.532
In order to vitrify
a patient,

36:05.567 --> 36:08.869
you have to perform
a median sternotomy, isn't that correct?

36:08.904 --> 36:10.571
So?
Closing that

36:10.605 --> 36:12.106
incision requires stitches.

36:12.140 --> 36:14.074
Like these.

36:14.109 --> 36:16.443
So you used a distinctive,

36:16.478 --> 36:18.846
unnecessarily
complicated style of suturing:

36:18.880 --> 36:22.449
the Interrupted Vertical
Mattress Suture.

36:22.484 --> 36:25.786
I'm not the only doctor
who does interrupted sutures.

36:25.820 --> 36:27.454
No, but being left-handed,

36:27.489 --> 36:30.090
you're the only one at CryoNova
who knots each suture

36:30.125 --> 36:32.693
on the left side as
opposed to the right

36:32.727 --> 36:36.830
as well as using a surgical knot
instead of a simple reef.

36:36.865 --> 36:38.933
Quite distinctive.
Like I said, you killed her.

36:38.967 --> 36:40.801
She wasn't dead.

36:40.835 --> 36:42.236
I would never kill her.

36:42.270 --> 36:44.204
Right, you just wanted
to keep her really cold.

36:44.239 --> 36:46.807
Your wife found out when
those new clients came in.

36:46.841 --> 36:50.744
She dumped her in that swamp.
Michelle killed her.

36:50.779 --> 36:53.714
I loved Maddie.

36:53.748 --> 36:55.416
She understood my work,

36:55.450 --> 36:58.218
we spent every day together
writing grants.

36:58.253 --> 37:01.288
But she didn't love you,
did she?

37:04.259 --> 37:06.994
I-I could have revived her.

37:07.028 --> 37:08.662
And her daughter.

37:08.697 --> 37:11.532
Maybe it would have taken
ten years or so,

37:11.566 --> 37:13.200
but...

37:15.403 --> 37:17.438
when she came back,

37:17.472 --> 37:19.540
she would've grown to love me.

37:26.748 --> 37:28.782
She just needed time.

37:32.988 --> 37:37.891
♪ I'm sitting on a gold mine

37:40.128 --> 37:43.864
♪ And all I gotta do is dig

37:47.669 --> 37:50.938
♪ But I'm waiting on

37:50.972 --> 37:56.076
♪ A landslide.

37:58.246 --> 38:00.014
(doorbell rings)

38:02.984 --> 38:05.019
Ooh.

38:08.156 --> 38:10.324
Azita, Armin.

38:10.358 --> 38:11.925
We were going to call you,

38:11.960 --> 38:14.294
but didn't know whether
you'd hang up or not.

38:14.329 --> 38:15.863
Oh, of-of course not.

38:15.897 --> 38:17.931
Uh, come in.
I'm actually,

38:17.966 --> 38:19.500
I'm just making
some tea.

38:19.534 --> 38:21.602
Ah, thank you.

38:21.636 --> 38:22.736
Who was at the...?

38:22.771 --> 38:24.238
Oh.

38:24.272 --> 38:26.407
Are you going to have a fit
and walk out again

38:26.441 --> 38:27.674
because I'm
staying for tea?

38:27.709 --> 38:30.811
We know how you feel.
Did you forget an insult or two?

38:30.845 --> 38:32.179
Why don't we all sit?

38:32.213 --> 38:34.014
You don't know how
we feel, Arastoo,

38:34.049 --> 38:36.417
'cause you never stop
judging us to notice.

38:36.451 --> 38:38.385
You've always been
a hothead.

38:38.420 --> 38:41.321
Ah, here we go.
Yes, here we go.

38:41.356 --> 38:46.093
Growing up, you were always
making the wrong decisions,

38:46.127 --> 38:47.728
getting into trouble.

38:50.331 --> 38:54.802
But you've grown into
such a wonderful man...

38:56.004 --> 39:00.474
so successful,
so fine.

39:07.382 --> 39:08.816
Whatever made you think

39:08.850 --> 39:11.585
we didn't notice
you'd grown up?

39:13.988 --> 39:16.623
You're making Cam cry, Azita.
Apologize.

39:16.658 --> 39:18.926
It's okay.

39:21.663 --> 39:24.131
But the other night,
with all the questions...

39:24.165 --> 39:25.332
Questions?

39:25.366 --> 39:27.201
Interest.

39:29.504 --> 39:32.806
Clearly, you're with
a wonderful woman,

39:32.841 --> 39:35.843
so brave to raise a child
on her own,

39:35.877 --> 39:37.444
so accomplished.

39:39.547 --> 39:42.549
You have good judgment, Arastoo.

39:46.921 --> 39:48.689
And excellent taste.

39:52.193 --> 39:54.628
You're not a teenager anymore.

39:54.662 --> 39:58.132
Let us be proud of you.
Let us be happy for you.

40:10.845 --> 40:12.212
I'm sorry.

40:13.281 --> 40:15.015
You should be.

40:17.552 --> 40:20.154
You look very comfortable
in those clothes.

40:20.188 --> 40:23.524
I imagine you spend
a lot of time here.

40:23.558 --> 40:24.925
Azita, it's none
of our business.

40:24.959 --> 40:27.227
And she's wearing
Arastoo's shirt.

40:27.262 --> 40:29.663
I cannot accept everything, Armin.
Can we at least have

40:29.697 --> 40:31.865
our tea before you start talking
about marriage?

40:31.900 --> 40:33.167
Marriage?

40:33.201 --> 40:37.437
Usually when a man introduces
a woman to his parents...

40:37.472 --> 40:39.039
You didn't think
that was an important fact?

40:39.073 --> 40:40.774
That's not how I feel.

40:40.808 --> 40:44.945
Someplace inside, you knew.

40:49.684 --> 40:51.552
Why don't you
grab the tea?

40:51.586 --> 40:53.253
I'm-I'm gonna go
grab a Scotch.

40:53.288 --> 40:54.321
Good idea.

40:54.355 --> 40:55.889
Yeah.
Yeah.

41:02.830 --> 41:06.600
BRENNAN: Sweets said that now the deputy
director is reviewing you

41:06.634 --> 41:07.834
for the promotion.

41:07.869 --> 41:10.404
Yeah, that's what
he told me, too.

41:10.438 --> 41:12.773
Why wouldn't you
mention that?

41:12.807 --> 41:15.609
Because nothing's definite yet,
Bones, that's why.

41:15.643 --> 41:18.212
Booth, you don't have
to worry about me. We can do this.

41:18.246 --> 41:20.375
There are many places

41:20.376 --> 41:21.275
I could work over there.

41:21.276 --> 41:23.498
In two years, 
Christine could be bilingual.

41:23.523 --> 41:24.451
Wait a second.

41:24.452 --> 41:27.888
Now you're just, you're getting
way ahead of yourself here.

41:27.922 --> 41:32.459
You always tell me
that I'm too rational,

41:32.493 --> 41:35.796
that dreaming is good.

41:36.965 --> 41:39.900
I'm not sure
this is such a good dream.

41:42.537 --> 41:44.538
I mean, from the military angle,

41:44.572 --> 41:46.206
them having me review
all these shootings

41:46.241 --> 41:49.443
and they've been looking
at my skill sets...

41:49.477 --> 41:51.878
Your gut is telling you
something, isn't it?

41:51.913 --> 41:53.113
Yeah.

41:53.147 --> 41:55.349
The base over there...

41:55.383 --> 41:58.318
it's a staging ground
for counterterrorism activity

41:58.353 --> 41:59.753
and covert operations.

42:01.489 --> 42:04.157
You think they might be asking
you to be a sniper again?

42:04.192 --> 42:05.759
I won't do it.

42:05.793 --> 42:07.728
I have a new life.
I have a family.

42:07.762 --> 42:09.596
They can't make me
do that again.

42:09.631 --> 42:12.799
You don't have to do anything
you don't want to, Booth.

42:19.448 --> 42:21.249
Right.

